---
title: Cheesy Mexican-Style Beef Stuffed Peppers with Guacamole, Pico de Gallo & Sour Cream
description: We see a bell pepper, and can’t help imagining it stuffed with all manner of deliciousness. A stuffed pepper is a sweet, savory, and hearty meal, and makes an especially easy and impressive family dinner. For this version, the peppers are stuffed with flavorful Mexican-seasoned ground beef and fluffy tomato rice. Top the stuffed peppers with our Mexican cheese blend, broil to bubbly perfection, then serve them with all your favorite toppings at the table: guacamole, pico de gallo, lime wedges, and sour cream! This recipe is double the typical servings, providing 4 servings and 8 servings for a 2 person and 4 person box respectively.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/65254fd3300e797a16c16f73-37b24c1b.jpeg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/65254fd3300e797a16c16f73.pdf
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/cheesy-mexican-style-beef-stuffed-peppers-65254fd3300e797a16c16f73
nutrition:
  calories: 800 kcal
  fat: 52 g
  saturated fat: 17 g
  carbohydrates: 51 g
  sugar: 8 g
  protein: 33 g
  fiber: 6 g
  sodium: 810 mg
author: Sara Heilman
time required: 45 minutes
cuisine: Central America
course: main course
servings: 2
---

Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 8 servings) and
preheat oven to 425 degrees.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #small pot{} (medium pot for 8) over
medium-high heat. Add @tomato paste{1%unit} and cook, stirring, until darkened
in color, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @white rice{3/4%ounce}, one of the @chicken stock concentrate{1} (two for
8), 1¼ cups @water{1 1/4%cups} (2¼ cups for 8), and a big pinch of @salt{pinch}.
Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is
tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in Step 4.

Meanwhile, wash and dry produce. Halve @green bell pepper{4%unit} lengthwise;
remove stems and seeds. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{3%cloves}. Quarter
@lime{2%unit}.

Place bell peppers on a #baking sheet{} (divide between two baking sheets
for 8 servings) and drizzle each half with @cooking oil{6%tsp}; rub to coat.
Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}. Arrange cut sides down; roast on top
rack (for 8, roast on top and middle racks, swapping rack positions halfway
through) until tender, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp} in a #large pan{} (for 8 servings, use two
large pans or cook in batches) over medium-high heat. Add
@ground beef{20%ounce}, @garlic{}, @Mexican spice blend{2%tablespoon},
remaining @chicken stock concentrate{2} (for 8, more), @salt{pinch}, and
@pepper{}. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through,
~{4-6%minutes}.

Using a #slotted spoon{}, transfer beef mixture to a #large bowl{}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{} (it's OK if rice has a little extra liquid); transfer
to bowl with beef mixture. Stir until thoroughly combined. Taste and season
with @salt{} and @pepper{} if desired.

Once bell peppers are done roasting, remove sheet from oven. Carefully flip
bell peppers and stuff each half with as much filling as will fit. Sprinkle with
@Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}.

Heat broiler to high or increase oven to 500 degrees.

Transfer stuffed peppers to top rack and broil or roast until cheese is melted
and bubbly, ~{2-4%minutes} (for 8 servings, broil or roast in batches).

> Watch carefully to avoid burning!

In a #small bowl{}, combine @guacamole{1/2%cup} and a squeeze of lime juice;
season with @salt{} and @pepper{} to taste.

Divide stuffed peppers between #plates{}. Top peppers with juice from two lime
wedges (four wedges for 8 servings). (TIP: If you like things spicy, add a few
dashes of hot sauce!) Place guacamole, @pico de gallo{4%ounce}, and
@sour cream{3%tablespoon} in separate #serving bowls{} and serve with remaining
lime wedges on the side.

> Ground beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.